{"type":"message","id":"f421c9cb","parentId":"eaf3a6a2","timestamp":"2026-03-24T15:34:36.121Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_6nq32fnmctn8_2","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Pulse: 2026-03-24 113316\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\nRejected: experiments/cfi_compression_test.ps1 (missing)\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLet me review the current state and determine what single concrete action to take.\r\n\r\nLooking at the goals:\r\n- Phase 0 COMPLETE: Sandbox foundation established\r\n- Phase 1 COMPLETE: Architecture cross-analysis + integration spec synthesized\r\n- CFI Analysis complete (new finding about 44.8% being noise)\r\n- Pending: CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n\r\nThe most actionable next step based on the CFI findings would be to implement the CFI-weighted compression experiment. The research showed that 44.8% of frequency-invariants have CFI=0 (pure noise) and only 5.7% have high CFI (>=0.7). \r\n\r\nThe pending action says:\r\n- [ ] CFI-weighted compression experiment (compare next-pulse prediction vs frequency baseline)\r\n\r\nThis is the logical next step. I should design and implement a simple experiment that:\r\n1. Takes the frequency-invariant analysis data\r\n2. Weights it by CFI scores\r\n3. Compares prediction quality vs frequency-only baseline\r\n\r\nLet me create a concrete experiment file that outlines this test. I need to be specific and actionable.\r\n\r\nActually, looking at the files mentioned:\r\n- `research/CFI_RESULTS.md` - contains the CFI analysis\r\n\r\nI should create an experiment script or document that implements the CFI-weighted compression and compares it to the frequency baseline. Let me create a `research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md` that outlines the methodology and then implement a test.\r\n\r\nWait, I need to think about what I can actually do in one pulse. The experiment would need:\r\n1. Access to the frequency-invariant data\r\n2. CFI scores\r\n3. A way to measure \"next-pulse prediction quality\"\r\n\r\nSince Breakaway is stateless, \"next-pulse prediction\" would be about whether the compression preserves information that would be useful for the next pulse's reconstruction.\r\n\r\nLet me create a concrete experiment design document that specifies exactly how to run this test, and then implement the core logic.\r\n\r\n\r\nI can build a Python script to execute the experiment directly using the data from CFI_RESULTS.md. This approach is more actionable than just documenting the methodology—I can actually run the compression comparison and get results in this pulse.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nThe CFI analysis revealed that 44.8% of frequency-invariants are pure noise (CFI=0) while only 5.7% are true causal anchors (CFI≥0.7). This suggests filtering by CFI could significantly improve compression quality over frequency-only methods.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate a CFI-weighted compression experiment script that compares CFI-filtered compression against frequency-only baseline, using the invariant data to measure prediction quality difference.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n`\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\nCFI-weighted compression will outperform frequency-only compression by filtering out metaprogramming noise artifacts (CFI=0) while preserving true causal invariants (CFI≥0.7).\r\n\r\n## Method\r\n\r\n### Data Source\r\n- `research/FREQUENCY_INVARIANTS.md` - frequency counts for each invariant\r\n- `research/CFI_RESULTS.md` - CFI scores per invariant\r\n\r\n### Baseline: Frequency-Only Compression\r\n```python\r\n# Top-N by frequency only\r\ntop_n_freq = sorted(invariants, key=lambda x: x.frequency, reverse=True)[:N]\r\n```\r\n\r\n### Experiment: CFI-Weighted Compression\r\n```python\r\n# Score = frequency * CFI (geometric combination)\r\nweighted_score = inv.frequency * inv.cfi_score\r\ntop_n_cfi = sorted(invariants, key=lambda x: x.frequency * x.cfi_score, reverse=True)[:N]\r\n```\r\n\r\n### Metrics to Compare\r\n1. **Mean CFI** of selected invariants (higher = more causal signal)\r\n2. **Noise ratio** (% with CFI=0)\r\n3. **Causal ratio** (% with CFI≥0.7)\r\n4. **Compression ratio** (bytes saved)\r\n\r\n## Expected Outcome\r\n| Metric | Frequency-Only | CFI-Weighted |\r\n|--------|-----------------|--------------|\r\n| Mean CFI | ~0.18 | >0.5 |\r\n| Noise % | 44.8% | <15% |\r\n| Causal % | 5.7% | >25% |\r\n\r\n## Next Pulse\r\n- Run actual comparison on real invariant data\r\n- Implement CFI filter in `pulse.ps1` compression step\r\nfile: research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md\r\n`\n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 0\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 11:33:42\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774366476119}}
